         <abstract>
            <p>U.S. corporations spend billions of dollars annually on corporate marketing activities, such as financial press advertising, analysts meetings, annual reports, publicity, etc. Little is known about the effects of such marketing activities. This paper reports an empirical analysis of financial press advertising and its effect on common stock prices. A positive, significant advertising impact was found under some stock market conditions.</p>
         </abstract>
